China Stocks: BYD, Construction Bank, Chongqing Changan, ICBC

-- B y   I r e n e   S h e n
-- 
2011-09-13T07:35:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-12/byd-merchants-bank-chongqing-changan-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, lost 1.1 percent to 2,471.31. The  CSI
300 Index (SHSZ300)  fell 1.1 percent to 2,720.28.  Banks:  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (601398
CH) dropped 1 percent to 4.14 yuan, the biggest decline since
Aug. 29.  China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (601939 CH) retreated 0.9
percent to 4.53 yuan.  Agricultural Bank of China Ltd. (601288)  (601288
CH) slid 0.4 percent to 2.57 yuan.  China’s central bank sold more than 20 billion yuan ($3.1
billion) of additional bills to ICBC, Construction Bank,
Agricultural Bank and some other lenders after they were judged
to have lent excessively, the Beijing News reported, citing an
unidentified person.  Anhui Water Resources Development Co. (600502 CH) rose 3.3
percent to 13.76 yuan, the biggest gain since Aug. 4. The
company won a contract worth of 1.6 billion yuan, according to a
statement to the Shanghai Stock Exchange.  BYD Co. (002594 CH), the Chinese automaker part-owned by
 Warren Buffett ’s  Berkshire Hathaway Inc ., plunged 6.3 percent to
21.13 yuan, the lowest close since its listing in Shenzhen on
June 30. The company’s shareholders approved a plan to sell
bonds, according to a statement to the Shenzhen Stock Exchange
on Sept. 9. The company said on Aug. 25 it plans to sell as much
as 6 billion yuan of bonds in China with a maturity of no longer
than 10 years.  Chongqing Changan Automobile Co. (000625 CH) slipped 1.4
percent to 4.13 yuan, its lowest close since April 28, 2009. The
automaker said August sales fell to 89,559 units from 114,297
units a year earlier, according to a statement to the Shenzhen
stock exchange.  Shanghai Maling Aquarius Co. (600073 CH) added 2.8 percent
to 10.40 yuan, the biggest gain since July 20. The company plans
to sell its 59.8 percent stake in a subsidiary that sells
poultry products and a 24 percent shareholding in an affiliate
that manufactures food cans, according to a statement to the
 Shanghai Stock Exchange  today.  To contact the Bloomberg News staff on this story:
